column6: Considered an invasive species in North America

A subspecies of red fox found in the Oregon Cascades and the Sierra Nevada. It is the only native red fox subspecies in California. It is likely one of the most endangered mammals in North America. Estimates suggest only 18 to 39 individuals remain in the wild.  The High Sierra fox shares most of its physical characteristics with the red fox, though it is slightly smaller. The tail tip is white and the back of the ears is black.
Monogamous! Males help raise their young.
3.1-6 lbs, 2 ft long. Born fully furred with eyes open.
Can be found almost anywhere on Earth. The world's most widespread raptor. Fly up to 190 mph.
0.67 -1.09 lbs. 5.1 in. Cliff swallows are extremely social songbirds that can be found in large nesting colonies reaching over 2,000 nests. Males and females look almost identical.
Prefer moist habitats and are freqiently found near meadows and rivulets.
the only bat in North America, north of Mexico, with large ears and leaf-like projections on the nose
The world's smallest leporid. The only native rabbit species in North America to dig its own burrow.
Rock squirrels are larger, heavier, and have longer, bushier tails than other ground squirrels
Females are 880 to 1,980 lb while males are 3,300–5,100 lb and measure 13–16 ft long. One of two species of elephant seal.
Weigh up to 370 lbs. Females live longer than males (35 vs 25 years). They can be found on both the Pacific and Atlantic coast.
The largest of the four surviving subspecies of elk (Cervus canadensis) in North America. Mature bulls weigh from 700 to 1,200 lb.
Adult males weigh 450 to 550 lbs and females weigh 375 to 425 lbs. A subspecies of elk found only in California.
The Rocky Mountain Elks are the largest elk in the elk subfamily. From there the elk ranges from 500-750 pounds
Most common squirrel in california. California ground squirrels live in burrows, which they excavate themselves. Some burrows are occupied communally, but each squirrel has its own entrance.
